[[Category:Humanism]]

An '''intrauterine pressure catheter''' ('''IUPC''') is a [[catheter]] used during [[labor induction|induction]] of [[childbirth|labor]] to measure the amount of the [[uterus]]'s [[uterine contraction|contractions]] by taking into account intrauterine [[pressure]] and contraction frequency, duration, and strength.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pregnancy.about.com/od/laborcomplications/ig/Labor---Birth-Interventions/Intrauterine-Pressure-Catheter.htm|title=Intrauterine Pressure Catheter|publisher=About.com|first=Robin|last=Elise Weiss}}</ref> This is mainly of use for an [[obstetrics|obstetrician]] or [[midwife]] who wants to determine the amount of [[oxytocin]] (labor-inducing medication) to use.
The IUPC measures uterine performance in [[Montevideo units]] and is largely praised amongst clinicians because it provides an objective, quantifiable report of uterine performance, without interference by maternal movements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uptodate.com/contents/insertion-of-intrauterine-pressure-catheters|title=Insertion of intrauterine pressure catheters|publisher=uptodate.com|first=Jaimey M|last=Pauli|first2= John T|last2=Repke}}</ref> The IUPC may also be used when internal fetal monitoring is used.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pregnancy.about.com/od/laborcomplications/ig/Labor---Birth-Interventions/Intrauterine-Pressure-Catheter.htm|title=Intrauterine Pressure Catheter|publisher=About.com|first=Robin|last=Elise Weiss}}</ref>
